title: Anet Magnetic Extruder Fan Frame KIS

description.text:
Anet Magnetic Extruder Fan Frame

Stressed by always unmounting the extruder fan just to have a look at the nozzle tube,
i searched for an solution. I found some, but i want to keep it as simple as possible. I found those 4 little flat magnets (4x12x1mm) and created this holder.

I split it in two frames, the thin frame (5mm) and the fat frame (12mm), but just because i wanted to use the original M3-30mm and M3-20mm machine screws.

You dont need the fat frame if you have shorter screws available, just print the thin frame twice and use them :)

The modell are designed, so the screwheads and magnets disappear inside of them,
making a flat surface and therefor a steady airflow.

You need:

4x Magnets, flat, 4x12x1mm
4x M3-20mm machine screws to mount the fan on the thin frame
2x M3-30mm machine screws to mount the fat frame to the extruder
some superglue to glue the magents in the frames

Little video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YLLGPxEzUFU

comments.text:
Nice and simple solution! Prints well.
Btw: Plenty of the cheapo china brushless motors (i.e. A2212) use 4x12x1 magnets.
Otherwise, if you can't find them, I guess any slim, square neodym magnet of similar size should do.

2x 3/4" pipe caps with 5mm hole drilled in center
2x 3/4" flex pipes / coolant pipes

title: Classic Car, Substitute 1971 Dodge Challenger Fender Clip, Wide Chrome "Spring Package"
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: I designed these for a friend that is restoring a 1971 Dodge Challenger, that had the "Spring Package" Wide Nose Chrome Moldings. The "Spring Package" is found on the 1971 Dodge Challenger only, and was a one year option. The clips are used to attached the two fender wide chrome moldings only. I created two different versions that were suitable for 3-D printing. I printed them in PETG at a 45° angle. This was a good compromise between minimal supports and strength. I think it's important to stay away from 0° as that would line up the the layers with the fender sheet metal and could lead to delamination. Due to outside temperatures I use PETG even though ABS does have a higher temperature profile it can have problems with layer adhesion. I did a little Torque testing with both designs in Polymax PLA and PETG and they all came in at about 17 in-lbs. Hope this helps the classic car community. If this helps please leave a comment and/or a maker picture.

This is a short video summarizing the build of a small arduino controlled night light built from RGB light strips, an ESP8266 based mini D1, a 3D printed base/dome, and a few support components.

While you can duplicate my build/case, I've included the Fusion360 file so that you can modify the case to best fit your specific needs - especially if you decide to create a larger night light with more than (9) LEDs.

The arduino code files I included in the files section create the Aurora Borealis (Northern Lights) and Raging Fire displays I show in the video. Since the mini-D1 has wifi capability, you could write your own arduino code that allows you to change the night light colors, speed, etc. via a web browser or even with an app that you write yourself. The possibilities are endless!

title: Ventilation kit for Flashforge Creator and Qidi printer

description.text:
As my printer is standing in my living room, inhaling the fumes isn't very nice (and probably not healthy). So I created this ventilation kit, using a vacuum hose, which I can hang out of my window. This decreases the fumes to a hardly noticeable level, so I am quite happy with the result.

The files contain

  • A 120 mm fan duct with threaded vacuum hose connector
  • An endcap for the other end of the vacuum hose to protect it

This is also needed:

  • A 120 mm PC fan, USB powered (AliExpress)
  • A 120 mm fan filter (from AliExpress, or you can print one)
  • A vacuum hose, inner diameter 40 mm, outer diameter 49 mm, thread distance 6 mm (AliExpress)
  • Aluminum plate 20 x 30 cm, thickness 1 mm (AliExpress)

Building the ventilation kit is straightforward:
Replace the left side window by the aluminum plate (cut to 24 x 20 cm), in the center of which an 11 cm diameter hole is drilled, and holes for attaching the fan and holes for attaching it to your printer's frame. Put the fan at the outside of the plate, the filter at the inside (there is not enough room to put the fan inside the printer). That's it!

description.text:
I recently purchased a Parrot Teleprompter for doing company training videos but bringing in my DSLR to the office every day with my big tripods, cables, battery packs and so on was starting to be a hassle. I always have a GoPro with me though and so I wanted to adapt this awesome mini teleprompter to GoPro awesomeness! This adapter plate simply slides onto the back of the Parrot 2 Teleprompter, you need to print out the generic 1/4" x 20 tripod plate below to stick on the bottom of the teleprompter in order to mount it on any tripod with a standard screw mount. I used 3M VHB double sided tape on the plate to ensure it wasn't going to fall off my tripod.

The GoPro is very wide angle so if you have it set on wide or medium FOV you will get horrible vignetting so the settings I use for my Hero 4 Silver or Black are 2.7K Linear FOV. 1080p also has the linear field of view setting but I like to have a little more image resolution in my videos in case I need to crop in post production. The linear FOV crops the image about 10% and takes out the extreme barrel distortion of the cameras lens. I designed this mod with vlogging in mind so the charging ports and SD card are totally accessible without removing the camera from the holder. A cool little bonus I didn't plan on was the camera fits just snug enough that with the camera mounted, you can power it on or off and make mode changes using the front button on the camera by gently pushing the camera forward against the back of the adapter. It works so sweet, its almost like I designed it that way! The other two buttons are exposed by design.

This is perfect for me while vlogging or doing quick location shoots for my Youtube channel. Throw it on a Joby pod, clamp it to a tree and you have a high resolution camera/teleprompter setup which works awesome. Really the only thing you need to finish this build is a 1/4" x 20 square nut available at Home Depot or Lowes or your favorite hardware store and some really decent double sided tape to mount the tripod plate. I used 20% infill but its solid enough I likely could have gotten away with less but your mileage may vary depending on your printers capabilities. ENJOY!

description.text: This is a little spinning toy I made for my nephew. It consists of three very different kinds of fish: Sawfish, Starfish and Shellfish. When it is turned upside down, the starfish doubles as a spinning top. Put it in the scallop and use the nose of the sawfish to spin the starfish in the shellfish.  See the instructions and the video for more information.

How to spin the starfish:
  • Take the scallop in one hand with the opening facing upward.
  • Place the starfish in the bearings on the scallop's edge with the gear facing towards you.
  • Take the sawfish in your other hand and place the nose at the gear of the starfish.
  • Hold the scallop parallel to the ground.
  • Pull the fish back and send the starfish spinning!
    • Check out the the video for how it's done: http://youtu.be/OXPx3ca7Yj0 Tips & Tricks: Playing with this thing will send hard plastic parts spinning through your room, so be careful! It will take a bit of practice until you get it spinning properly. Try holding the rack parallel to the gear and pull in a straight line. I also added a puller that should be a bit more effective. Use it instead of the sawfish if you want a bit more spinning action and less of the fish. How this thing was made: The body of the sawfish and the scallop were both created in Sculptris. It was the first time I tried this program so I'm quite happy with the results. The starfish, the sawfish-nose and the puller were made in OpenSCAD. I used Leemon Baird's public domain gear library for the gear and racks. The final composition was done in Blender. Printing instructions: The models printed well for me in the provided orientation, some support structures will be necessary. The gear is faced down and may need a bit more cleaning, depending on your support structures.

How to assemble

  • 4 M3x16 screws
  • 4 M3 nuts
  • 1 M4x50 screw
  • 1 M4 nylock nut

Print both halves of the big clip, put them together so the holes line up, then slide the bulldog clip in sideways. Once the bulldog clip is in, it should be springy.

Next, line up the holes on the big clip with the holes on the back of the holster. Slide in the M4 screw and use the nylock nut to hold everything together.

Once you have the back assembled, sandwich the walls between the cap and the back and screw it all together with the M3 screws.

title: Bowden Hotend Clamp for Vulcanus V1

description.text:
I didn't see the point in using a direct drive extruder on the Vulcanus V1, especially the one that was suggested since that extruder probably wouldn't work with flexible filaments, plus bowden extruders are faster. So I made this hotend clamp that allows you to use a bowden extruder (with a hotend that is designed to be used w/ a bowden extruder).

This clamp should prevent the bowden tube from slipping out of the hotend, provided that your hotend has a bowden tube fitting built into it like mine (E3D V6), and it should also prevent the bowden tube from getting bent too much near the hotend, which can sometimes cause under-extrusion.

To install, you will need two M3x20mm screws, two M3 hex nuts, and the "CoreXY_X-Carriage" part designed by Vulcaman for his Vulcanus V1 printer.

I designed this to fit the E3D V6 hotend, I can't guarantee it will fit any of its clones.

title: Monoprice maker select plus IIIP Rear Brace (at the back)

description.text:
I was looking for a brace that was positioned at the rear so that the threaded rod does not stick out in front. I couldn't find one so I tried to learn to create things through fusion 360 and came up with this. I am not sure if this works well and I do not guarantee that it improves your prints but I'm sharing it nonetheless :)

Feel free to use and modify as you please.

You will need the following after printing these thingys...

2 pcs 400 - 410 mm M8 (5/16") metal threaded rod
2 pcs M5 x 16 screws -- to replace the lower rear screws at the back
8 pcs M3 x 12 screws -- because the the other screws on the side and the bottom will not be long enough anymore
6 pcs M8 hex nuts -- to hold the rods
2 pcs M8 nylon hex nuts -- to be placed at the bottom (no slippage)

Optional: heat shrink tubes to cover the threaded rods (I used a combination of black and red)

About the Nuts: There are 2 kinds of nut holders in the STL files (those hex shaped thingys with a half dome). One has a big dome while the other has a smaller dome. You need 8 of them printed. You can mix and match whichever you think is best. I printed for myself 4 small and 4 large. The small ones are used at the outer ends of the rods while the 4 large ones are used at the inner part of the rods.

The procedure is:

  1. Print the thingys (make sure to flip them in your slicer before printing)
  2. Buy the stuff above (will be less than $10)
  3. Remove the screws from your printer
  4. Loosely connect the upper and lower parts with the rods
  5. Connect the parts to the printer
  6. Tighten all the screws

By the way, some of my pictures are the first versions of prints (before I fixed slight defects in the design). I fixed these defects in the final STL files that I uploaded here.

Also uploaded a .STEP file of the entire design for those who are interested in modifying my version.

You may also be interested on the middle foot thingy... https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2824127

A tool to that allow you to wipe your baby ass.

Meet Skip-E! This robot is an idea for a newly designed Chip-E. Instead of being a biped, Skip-E has two feet that are used to 'skip' and two wheels for locomotion. These two wheels are only 180 degrees to match the rotation of the 180 degree servos, but the obvious problem is overcome by its ability to skip.

By lifting its body off of the ground on its feet, Skip-E is then able to freely rotate his wheels, allowing them to be reset into whatever position you choose. To move forward, Skip-E lifts up, puts its wheels back, and then lowers and rolls forward, repeating the process.

We hoped to come up with a new approach to a fun robot that can be programmed to have many features. By having two feet and two half-wheels, Skip-E becomes more versatile and opens the door for more tricks, dances, and geeky robot fun.

We were looking to transform the cute Chip-E robot into something new and different. Still much like a toy, Skip-E does take up a little more room, but his design can be tweaked to help that. Still being prototyped, he has some balance issues and some better ways of attaching its components can be developed, but Skip-E provides a different look at what a toy robot can be.

title: TronXY X3 / X3A E3D V5 J-Head Mount with 5015 blower duct
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I've been getting great results from my TronXY X3A printer and have been using a regular 40mm fan with a duct. Everyone is raving about blowers so I think I'm going to give it a shot. This mount will fit the TronXY X3/X3A with stock autolevel sensor and Chinese J-Head E3D V5 hot end. Also fits a 5015 blower and allows angulation and height adjustment.

Please look at my profile and see my other E3D mount with 40mm fan and duct. The hot end mount on that design is the same as this one so if you already have the fan/duct set-up you can upgrade to this blower by printing only the blower mount and blower duct. The blower mount needs no print support if place with the large face on the bed. The blower duct also needs no support if printed as shown in the last pic.

Finally, I got a chance to test last night. It works well and you can feel the difference in the volume of air compared to a fan/duct, but ultimately makes little difference in the overall print quality so in my opinion either fan/duct or blower/duct systems are fairly equal.

Hardware/assembly requirements: (2 ea) M4 x 20mm hex socket screws and nuts for blower mount, (5 ea) M3 x 16mm hex socket screws and nuts to mount the hot end to the base, the blower mount to the base, and the autolevel sensor to the base.

if you want to rework the whole thing, check my other things for the sawn off shell and the standard 12 ga shell. (I suggest for the 12 ga shell that if you do a boolean difference, that you increase is scale to 107% first)

description.text: This is a set of heart-shaped pieces that nest together as the base for a Valentine's Day craft project.

Process
Using the "Heart Cookie Cutter" thing, as well as a heart-shaped cookie cutter from home, as an inspiration, I traced a heart shape in Inkscape. That SVG file was then taken into 123D Design, where the different L shapes were swept around the profile to generate the final geometry.
If you look closely, there's a small glitch on the side of each shape (on the left of one, the right of the other) where the sweep operation couldn't quite finish completely. I could only go 99.99% around the path.
Assembly
This is pretty simple. Print both pieces, and they fit together. There's no friction, but the two sides do need to be aligned pretty closely - so if you're using these with small children you may need to help them a bit. Maybe a future version will bevel the mating faces a bit to make it easier.
Please note
Although these pieces use a cookie cutter as their inspiration, I would not recommend using these files as cookie cutters. The thin edge that would cut the dough is actually two filaments of plastic, which can trap dough and would be very hard to wash clean. As I understand the chemistry involved, it is actually not recommended to use any 3d-printed parts in food processes without sealing and doing other prep work. Be careful, do your research, proceed at your own risk, etc.

This mount has a larger center hole and wire pass through as well as 5mm stand-offs to allow more cooling air to exit the fuselage.
